ht im\nprovement over May were seen\nyesterday in preliminary reports.\nGross operating revenues for the\nfirst three weeks of June show a\ngain of $332,000 over the cor\nresponding period in May, $260,-\n000 of the amount coming from\nfreight and $72,000 from increased\npassenger traffic.\nOficials here pointed out that\noperating costs are being cut at\nevery possible point and that as\na consequence June net will un\ndoubtedly show a decided increase\nover net of the preceding month.\nUp to May 31, 1930, the company\nwas behind $500,000 in net operat\ning income for the first five\nmonths compared with the corres\nponding period last year. If the\npresent trend can be maintained,\nthe road stands a chance of re\ncouping, before the end of the\nyear, the losses suffered in the\nfirst half.\n\u201cCrop conditions along the\nFrisco lines are excellent,\u201d J. M.\nKurn, president of the road said\nin a statement given out in St.\nLouis yesterday. \u201cCotton is good\nand will compare with our best\nyears. Com too, promises a high\nyield, while in wheat we are\nahead of last year.\n\u201cPresent trade depression, I be\nlieve has reached its lowest point,\nand I look for a gradual improve\nment in industry during the latter\npart of the year.\u201d\nThe St. Louis-San Francisco\nRailway Co. has acquired control\nof hte Gulf, Texas and Western\nrailroad, a line of 100 miles in\nWestern Texas,at a cost of $1,800,-\n000, according to Mr. Kurn. Ac\nquisition of the road by Frisco\nwas approved by the stockholders\nof the company in 1929. The line\nwill be leased.\nTwo new* stretches of track to\nconnect the road with the present\nline to the St. Louis-San Frtn\ncisco and Texas branch of the\nFrisco will be built. The new\nroad was built originally in 1908\nwith a projected total route of\n500 miles. It has been in the\nhands of receivers since 1921.\nGRAINS LOWER\nCHICAGO, July 7 (IN. B.).\u2014Grains\nopened lower today. Wheat waa off\n%\u00aelo; corn. %G>%c, and oats, %O%c.\nOpening prices:\nWhsat \u2014July, 89%c: September. 92%\n\u00a993c; December, 99\u00a999%c.\nCorn \u2014July, 75c; September, 73%c;\nDecember. 17%087%c.\nOat\u00bb\u2014July, 33%c; September 35%\n35%c; December, 39%\u00a939%c.\nFOREIGN BONDS\nFrench 4e 40%\nFrench 5s 40\nFrench Premium 5s 52%\nFrench Internal Is 39%\nBelgian Premium 5s 28%\nBelgian Reetoration Is 27\nBritish War Loan 51 416\nBritish Victory 423%\nItalian Cons 5s 43\nMONDAY, JULY 7, 1030 v\n-Prev. i 960-, Nam* and N*t\nHigh Low Dividend Rate High Low 1:13 Ch'Ko\n141\u20191 interetat* Eauld* 7 7J* 7Ji\u2014 ?4\nMH* int H Mill* BJ4 8h- Ui\nUi */l Intercom Fet Ji Ji Ji\u2014 Ji\n24 17Ji Internal Pet 1.... 18H 18 18)i\u2014 Ji\n48JJ 32J3 Int Snoeroower 1* 3U4 3Ui 31Ji\u2014 Ji\n7Ji 2Ji inter Prod* 4Ji 4Ji <Ji+ Ji\n19Ji \u00abJi Int Utilities 8.... 14Ji 14Ji 14Ji\n27 12 Irvins Air Ch 1U 14 13? i 14 Ji\n9!i 5 Irving Air Ch ws.. 4?i 4Ji 4Ji\u2014 J-4\n1 7Jf Italian Sun A 10 10 10 Ji\n9?i 4J( Italian Sun deb rt 4B 4 4J4\n3 Ui Klrbv Petrol IJi Ui U 4\n4Ji Ui Leonard Oil.- Hi Hi Hi\n27 HJi Lib McNeil A Lib 14 14 14 Ji\n20>\u00bb 3?i Loew'e inc war... BJi 9ii B'i- Ji\n5 2 La Land 2Ji 2Ji- Ji\nJi Ji Magdalena 8....\u00bb- Ji Ji Ji\n57J+ 29\u00ab Mar Midld 1.20... 3GJi 30Ji 30Ji- Ji\n3Ji 1 Mavis Botl Hi Hi Ui\n22Ji 105* Memnhla NG 14Ji l<Ji 14Ji\n30 7 Metro Ch Sts.... 6 6 6\n16? i BJi Mattis AMS 1.20. 13Ji 13Ji 13H+ Ji\n295 i 24 Mid W*st Stt Utl. 25H 15Ji -5H- Ji\ne8 25Ji Mid W Util s%b.. 27Ji 27 27 Ji\n365 i 15 Mo K Pip* Llo*b 26 25Ji 25Ji- Ji\n12J\u00bb 7J< Nat Amir 2 7Ji 7Jj 7Ji\u201c Ji\n2t> 15 Nat Fam Bps 2.. 15Ji 15Ji 15Ji\u20143Ji\n30 11 Nat Inv 12J< 12 12 h\n103 H lOOJi Nat PAL 6pf ICBJi 112} t 102},+ Ji\n14Ji 12 Nat Short T....... HJt IHi 14H\nlOJi 3h Nat Un Radio.... 5Ji 5 5Ji\n3Ji 2? 8 N*w Brad Oil J 4. 2Ji 2Ji 2h- Ji\n914 65Ji N J Zinc n 2 67 67 67 Ji\n14H\u00bb 19 Newmont Mln 4a. 85 85 85 \u2014l4\n16Ji lOJg N I Petrol i 114 114 114+ Hi\n18 7 NY RA B Line.. 104 10Ji 1041 J\u00bb\n1174 H3Ji N T Tel of 1164 1154 06J2+2\n244 15Ji Nia A Hud Pw .41 164 16Ji 164- Ji\n64 4 Nia Hud F Awar. 44 44 44- 4\n444 20Ji Noranda Mine* 8. 244 24 24 -4\n5 2 N A Avia A war. 2?g 24 24\n44 24 North Europe Oil. 24 24 24- 4\n1834 138 No Sta Pw A 8... 1414 1414 1414+ 4\n14 Ji Ohio Copper. 4 4 4\n764 624 Ohio 011 2a 65* s 65 65\n114 74 Oilstocks Lt A4a 8 8 8\n13 34 Outboard B 54 54 54\n28? i 26 Pac Gas pf 14... 274 274 274+ 4\n24 4 Pandem OU 4 Ji 4\n13Ji 4 Paramt Cab \u00ab*b. <4 <Ji 144\n164 10Ji Pennroad vtc 114 11 11 Ji\n354 73 Penn Water 3.... 75?\u00bb 75\u00bb\u00bb 754- 24\n254 Peo Lt A 2.40.... 30 30 30\n105 85 Pepperell Mfg 8.. 88 88 88 +\u2018l4\nHearst Consolidated Stock Issue\n\nAvailable to Public Today\nBy B. C. FORBES\nToday the American public\nhave opportunity to become\npart-owners of the greatest pub\nlishing business in the world.\nHearst Consolidated Publica\ntions, Inc., owning 13 highly\nprofitable Hearst properties, is\noffering 7 per cent cumulative\npreferred stock which, in addi\ntion to the 7 per cent return,\nwill share equally with the com\nmon stock up to an additional\n3 per cent after $1.75 is paid on\nthe common.\nPays Up to 19 Per Cent\nThus the investor may receive\nas much as 10 per cent on his\nmoney\u2014if he subscribes for the\nissue now. before it is traded in\non the market at higher than\nthe offering price of $25 per\nshare.\nThe earnings on this issue\nhave averaged during the last\nfour years 3.14 times the an\nnual 7 per cent dividend re\nquirements.\nNot only so, but the profits\nhave increased each year, ris\ning from $10,009,806 in 1926 to\n$12,854,627 last year, when the\ndividend requirements were\nearned 3.67 times.\nWill List Stock\nApplication will be made to\nlist the stock on the New York\nCurb the Chicago Stock Ex\nchange, and the San Francisco\nStock EYC.ha.ngF\nOs the total issue of 2,000,000\nshares now being offered, 400,-\n000 shares have been reserved\nfor officers and employes, an\nobjective Mr. Hearst long has\nhad in mind. Many leading\ncorporations have found em\nploye-stock ownership advan\ntageous to all concerned, in\ncluding outside stockholders.\nGeneral Motors, the Pennsyl\nvania railroad, American Tele\nphone and Telegraph, United\nStates Steel Corporation, Gen\neral Electric, New York Cen\ntral, Standard Oil of California\n(and other Standard Oil com\npanies), International Harves\nter, American Tobacco. West\nern Union, Procter and Gamble,\nSwift and Company, Eastman\nKodak are among Qotably suc\ncessful companies that have\ninterested their employes in\nbuilding up the business by\nhaving them become financially\ninterested.\nSuch results as those already\noutlined having been attained\nduring the years the Hearst\nemployes did not enjoy the\nprivilege of stock ownership,\nsurely it is reasonable to fig\nure that even better results\nwill be brought about now that\na new incentive has been fur\nnished.\nTakes Priority\nIt is worth noting that Mr.\nHearst personally will not draw\na cent in dividends on the com\nmon stock he owns until 7 per\ncent has been paid on the new\npreferred.\nSince this new investment\ncombines with its 7 per cent\nregular payment the possibility\nof an extra 3 per cent, it con\nstitutes a safe investment plus\na valuable speculative attrac\ntion.\nRequests for the shares may\nbe made at any of the offices I\nNItHW\nNAMES HEADS\nThe board of directors of the\nNorwich Union Indemnity Com\npany has elected Hart Darlington,\nmanager of the Norwich Union\nFire Insurance Society, as chair\nman of the board; H. L. Callanan,\nformerly vice president, as presi\ndent and general manager, and\nC. E. Anderson and C. A. Barkie\nvice presidents of the company.\nH. L. Kidder continues as vice\npresident and secretary in charge\nof underwriting, and P. H. Guil\nfoil as vice president in charge\nof claims. Thus the operations of\nthe company will be continued as\nheretofore without change under\nthe officials and organization that\nfor a number of years have so\nsatisfactorily conducted its busi\nness.\nBy this election Mr. Darlington\nis given a new title, but his posi\ntion in the company is not ma\nterially changed. He has been a\ndirector since the company was\norganized, and, as general attor\nney of the Norwich Union Fire\nInsurance Society in the United\nStates, has naturally taken a part I\nin formulating the general poli\ncies of its subsidiary.\nPresident Callanan entered, the\ninsurance business as an accoun\ntant of the American Bonding\nCompany in its New York office\nin 1906, and when the Fidelity\nand Deposit Company purchased\ncontrol of that company in 1912\nhe went with the casualty depart\nment of the Fidelity Deposit in\nthe accounting and statistical divi\nsions. In 1915 he became chief\naccountant in the New York office\nof the Hartford Accident and In\ndemnity Company. He served in\nthe Navy during the war. When\nthe Norwich Union Indemnity was\norganized he became assistant to\nthe treasurer, was made treasurer\nin 1923 and vice president and\ntreasurer in 1926. Yesterday his\nprivate office was full of beauti\nful flowers sent in with congratu\nlations by his friends.\n_Prev. IHO-. Name and Wet\nHf\u00abh Low Dividend Rate Hlrh Low l:lt Ch'Se\n124 74 Pierce Gov 14... 84 84 M+ 4\n274 20\u2019/$ Plymouth 011 2... -64 26'a 264+ 4\n164 84 Pr A Whitley 103* 104 104- M\n44 35 Pr A Whit of 1... 384 iB4 3814- M\n274 15 Pub Utfl war...., 14 154 154- 4\n74 3 Ralnb Lu B 0f.... 3 3 3\n20\u00bbi 124 Reliable Sts 5%b. 14 13 14 Yi\n114 54 Rossie 1nter...... 74 74 74\n84 34 Ryan Con Pet.... 44 44 44- 4\n\u25a034 183* St. Reais Pan 1... 214 214 214- 4\n1034 54 Seaboard Util 6 6 6 4\n124 54 Seine Indus. 64 6 i+ 4\n94 5 Shattk Denn Min. .'4 54 W+ 4\n20 84 Shenendoah 93i 95* 94\u2014 4\n484 33 Shenand cv Df 8.. 394 394 394+ 4\n344 154 Silica Gel vtc 154 154 154- *4\n250 1374 Smith AO 2 196 196 196 +1034\n18 14 South Coast 14 14 14\n264 23 So Col Pw A 2... 24 24 24\n84 44 South Coro 6 6 6 4\n17 9 Southld R0y!...